# Agent Handoff Contract

All agents in the OpenBook Author studio accept and produce this schema.

## Router Handoff (input to execution agents)

```yaml
issue: <number>
title: <string>
classification: bug | feature | docs | refactor | test | design | unknown
confidence: <0.00–1.00>
agent: debug-agent | feature-agent | docs-agent | refactor-agent | test-agent | ui-agent
priority: low | medium | high | critical
estimated_scope: small | medium | large | epic
escalate: true | false
recommendation: <string | null>  # required when escalate is true
relevant_adrs: []  # full slugs, e.g. ADR-0001-guidebook-block-model — from @architecture-memory
deliverables:
  - <item>
success_criteria:
  - <criterion>
context:
  labels: []
  linked_files: []
  summary: <1–3 sentences>
lane: product | quality | knowledge | infrastructure
merge_lane: product | infrastructure  # which PR bucket — Dispatch and Merge Manager use this, not inference
ownership: []  # files or directories this task will touch — primary orchestration key
parallel_group: null | <area-id>  # semantic ownership area, e.g. editor, epub-import, docs
parallel_safe: true | false
conflicts_with:
  - issue: <number> | task: <string>
    reason: <string>  # e.g. Both modify RichEditor.tsx
wave: null | <wave-id>  # batch wave from @project-manager-agent, e.g. wave-a
queue_after: []  # issue numbers or task ids that must complete before starting
workflow:
  - <current-agent>
  - merge-manager-agent
  - review-agent
  - pr-creator-agent
```

### Orchestration principle

**Orchestrate by ownership, not by issue number.** Do not ask “Can these issues run together?” Ask “Will these agents touch the same parts of the codebase?”

### Router orchestration fields

| Field | Meaning |
|-------|---------|
| `lane` | Permanent lane — agents **within** a lane coordinate with each other (see below). |
| `merge_lane` | PR bucket at merge time: `product` (app code, templates, product docs) or `infrastructure` (`.cursor/rules/`, GitHub workflows, agent automation). Dispatch and Merge Manager use this field — do not infer from `lane` alone. |
| `ownership` | Files/directories this task will likely touch. Primary key for overlap detection. Execution agents may touch additional files; update in Execution Handoff via `files_touched`. |
| `parallel_group` | Semantic ownership area (e.g. `editor`, `epub-import`, `export-tests`, `docs`). Tasks in the same `parallel_group` on the **product** lane serialize; other lanes use file overlap only. |
| `parallel_safe` | `true` when this task may start now with no `queue_after` blockers. `false` when it must wait. |
| `conflicts_with` | Other issues or PM subtasks that share `ownership`. Populated even when still `parallel_safe` vs non-conflicting work. |
| `wave` | Batch wave id from `@project-manager-agent` (e.g. `wave-a`). `null` for solo or router-only triage. |
| `queue_after` | Issue numbers or task ids that must complete before this task starts. |

### Permanent lanes

| Lane | Purpose | Typical agents |
|------|---------|----------------|
| **product** | Features, bugs, editor, export | `feature-agent`, `debug-agent`, `review-agent`, `merge-manager-agent` |
| **quality** | Tests, accessibility, performance | `test-agent`, `ui-agent`, `review-agent` |
| **knowledge** | Docs, ADRs, research | `docs-agent` |
| **infrastructure** | Cursor rules, GitHub workflows, automation | `docs-agent`, `project-manager-agent`, `merge-manager-agent` |

### Cross-lane rules

- Agents **within** a lane coordinate with each other (ownership overlap, `queue_after`).
- Agents **across** lanes only meet at `@merge-manager-agent`.
- **Product never waits for infrastructure** unless there is an actual dependency (e.g. a new handoff field the product agent must read).

### Parallel rules by lane

| Lane | Parallel rule |
|------|---------------|
| **product** | One active task per overlapping `ownership` file |
| **quality** | Usually parallel; serialize only on in-flight product-file overlap |
| **knowledge** | Rarely conflicts; serialize on identical doc paths |
| **infrastructure** | Serialize on `.cursor/rules/` or workflow file overlap |

### Waves

Batch work by wave, not by issue count. Each wave may include product + quality + knowledge lanes, then merges before the next wave:

```
Wave A → product + quality + knowledge → merge (by merge_lane) → Wave B
```

### Safety signals

| Signal | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| 🟢 Safe | Different `ownership` areas and lanes — run together |
| 🟡 Coordinate | Related scope but non-overlapping files — UI may propose while feature codes |
| 🔴 Queue | Same `ownership` file on product lane — serialize |

## Execution Handoff (output from execution agents → review-agent)

```yaml
issue: <number>
source_agent: <agent-id>
lane: product | quality | knowledge | infrastructure
merge_lane: product | infrastructure
status: complete | blocked | needs_human
changes_summary: <what was done>
files_touched: []
deliverables_completed: []
success_criteria_met: []
adrs_consulted: []  # full ADR slugs read and followed
architecture_change: true | false
adr_proposal: null  # or { id: ADR-0005-short-slug, title: "...", action: new|supersede, supersedes: ADR-XXXX-short-slug }
open_questions: []
next_agent: review-agent
```

## Review Handoff (output from review-agent)

```yaml
issue: <number>
source_agent: review-agent
verdict: approved | changes_requested | blocked
findings: []
security_flags: []
a11y_flags: []
adr_compliance: pass | adr_missing | adr_conflict
next_agent: <execution-agent-id> | pr-creator-agent
```

### Review routing (`next_agent`)

- `needs_human` or empty `files_touched` (planning gate) → `next_agent` is the execution handoff `source_agent`
- `changes_requested` or `blocked` → `next_agent` is the execution handoff `source_agent`
- `status: complete`, tests pass, `verdict: approved` → `next_agent: pr-creator-agent`

### ADR compliance gate

When `architecture_change: true` in the execution handoff:

- `pass` — `adrs_consulted` shows Accepted ADRs were followed, or `adr_proposal` is present for merge
- `adr_missing` — architectural change with no ADR coverage
- `adr_conflict` — implementation contradicts an Accepted ADR without supersede proposal
